{"data":[{"type":"questionAttempts","id":"17612154","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionAttempts/17612154"},"attributes":{"position":0,"marks":1,"score":0,"answeredAt":"2025-09-30T14:18:31+09:30","options":[1],"response":null,"finalizedAt":"2025-09-30T14:18:31+09:30"},"relationships":{"user":{"data":{"type":"users","id":"50098"}},"questionSession":{"data":null},"session":{"data":null},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"16252"}},"bookmark":{"data":null}}}],"included":[{"type":"questions","id":"16252","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questions/16252"},"attributes":{"optionProportions":[0.02,0.02,0.02,0.88,0.05]},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"8943"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"74620"}}}},{"type":"items","id":"8943","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/items/8943"},"attributes":{"contentType":"question"},"relationships":{"content":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"16252"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"60114"}},"tags":{"data":[{"type":"tags","id":"67"},{"type":"tags","id":"71"},{"type":"tags","id":"76"},{"type":"tags","id":"4936"},{"type":"tags","id":"4942"},{"type":"tags","id":"4950"},{"type":"tags","id":"8094"},{"type":"tags","id":"8108"},{"type":"tags","id":"8541"},{"type":"tags","id":"8542"},{"type":"tags","id":"9990"}]},"contributions":{"data":[{"type":"contributions","id":"21280"},{"type":"contributions","id":"21282"}]}},"meta":{"canRevise":false,"canManage":false,"canDelete":false}},{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"74620","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionRevisions/74620"},"attributes":{"stem":"\u003Cp\u003EThe immune system undergoes various changes with advancing age, a process known as immunosenescence. These changes affect both innate and adaptive immunity.\u003C/p\u003E","stemQuestion":"Which one of the following best describes a consequence of age-related changes in the immune system?","responseType":"sba","marks":1,"options":["Increased production of naive T cells","Enhanced vaccine responses","Decreased susceptibility to infections","Increased inflammatory state with reduced immune function","Improved antibody diversity"],"correctOptions":[3],"correctResponses":null,"explanation":"\u003Cp\u003EWith ageing, there is an \u003Cstrong\u003Eincreased inflammatory state with reduced immune function\u003C/strong\u003E. This paradoxical situation involves chronic low-grade inflammation (inflammaging) alongside deteriorating immune responses. This contributes to increased susceptibility to infections and poor vaccine responses in elderly individuals.\u003C/p\u003E        \u003Cp\u003EThe incorrect options can be explained:\u003C/p\u003E    \u003Cul\u003E        \u003Cli\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EIncreased production of naive T cells\u003C/strong\u003E - Thymic involution actually leads to decreased production of naive T cells with age\u003C/p\u003E\u003C/li\u003E        \u003Cli\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EEnhanced vaccine responses\u003C/strong\u003E - Vaccine responses typically decline with age due to reduced T and B cell function\u003C/p\u003E\u003C/li\u003E        \u003Cli\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EDecreased susceptibility to infections\u003C/strong\u003E - The elderly have increased susceptibility to infections due to declining immune function\u003C/p\u003E\u003C/li\u003E        \u003Cli\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EImproved antibody diversity\u003C/strong\u003E - B cell diversity and function typically decline with age\u003C/p\u003E\u003C/li\u003E    \u003C/ul\u003E        \u003Cp\u003EThese age-related changes in immunity contribute to increased susceptibility to infections, reduced vaccine effectiveness, and higher rates of cancer and autoimmune conditions in elderly populations.\u003C/p\u003E","optionExplanations":null,"learningPoints":["Immunosenescence leads to decreased immune function and increased susceptibility to infections with age.","Ageing is associated with chronic low-grade inflammation called inflammaging.","The elderly have reduced vaccine responses due to decreased T cell and B cell function."],"references":["Ma S, Wang C, Mao X, Hao Y. B Cell Dysfunction Associated With Aging and Autoimmune Diseases. Front Immunol. 2019 Feb 27;10:318. doi: 10.3389/fimmu.2019.00318. PMID: 30873171; PMCID: PMC6400972.","Goronzy JJ, Weyand CM. Immune aging and autoimmunity. Cell Mol Life Sci. 2012 May;69(10):1615-23. doi: 10.1007/s00018-012-0970-0. Epub 2012 Apr 1. PMID: 22466672; PMCID: PMC4277694.","Weyand CM, Goronzy JJ. Aging of the Immune System. Mechanisms and Therapeutic Targets. Ann Am Thorac Soc. 2016 Dec;13 Suppl 5(Suppl 5):S422-S428. doi: 10.1513/AnnalsATS.201602-095AW. PMID: 28005419; PMCID: PMC5291468."]},"relationships":{"itemRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"60114"}},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"16252"}},"stemMedia":{"data":[]},"explanationMedia":{"data":[]}}},{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"60114","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/itemRevisions/60114"},"attributes":{"createdAt":"2024-12-25T22:21:26+10:30","updatedAt":"2024-12-25T22:57:37+10:30"},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"8943"}},"content":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"74620"}}},"meta":{"canDelete":false}},{"type":"tags","id":"67","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/67"},"attributes":{"emoji":"","name":"Basic Science","synonyms":null,"description":null,"position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":null},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"5"}},"heading":{"data":null}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"71","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/71"},"attributes":{"emoji":"","name":"Junior","synonyms":null,"description":"Suitable for a junior, pre-clinical medical student","position":0,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":null},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"6"}},"heading":{"data":nu